title: For Sale:  RARE Beechwood Original Czech VZ 58 with Zahal and MOre!
postcontent:
If you are into VZ's then...THIS IS THE ONE YOU WANT!

CzechPoint does not produce these rifles on a regular basis. In the past, mind you they have produced around 12 per year. This is a fact that I have in writing from CzechPoint. That alone makes this unfired rifle (except 15 - 25 rounds to zero after manufacture) VERY Special Indeed. The Beech was used for a Very short period of time during 1959-60? You can find pieces and parts of un-matching sets on the internet, or even re-manufactured wood. This is original A Gradel wood used in assembly at the CzechPoint facility. After that time the Czechs found it more cost effective and faster to use a mixture of compressed wood and resin composite (most of what you see today).

Times are changing and who knows what the future holds for these rifles. The VZ stands alone in it's class. It looks like an AK, but just looks...it is IN NO WAY LIKE AN AK!  Do your research. This rifle will out perform any AK out there. Side by side. Not a SINGLE part is interchangeable. They also are milled receivers, short pistons and striker fired (like a Glock). There are many other differences, but looking them up is half the fun!

What else makes this listing so special? Well, I am also including a "pimped out" version by including FAB furniture as well! This includes the folding tactical Stock with all the adjustments and inside storage. You can have it your way. I have pics of both. I am listing the photo of the original in the CzechPoint box with it's 2 magazines, tool kit, bayonet and OH YES! the sticker! BUT WAIT THERE'S MORE!  I am also including the rare bipod and a really really rare night sight kit / attachment that still holds a glow!

I paid CzechPoint $1,300 for the rifle. I did not fire it. I purchased the Zahal "pimp out accessories"  and put them on and took some photos. I found individually the rare Bipod and night sights. I bought the magnetic rail mount for the receiver and a red dot. OH! I didn't mention that above. The rail uses a really strong magnet and supposedly returns to zero since it only has one place to rest.  Well... that's all for one price and it is a firm price. You will NEVER find a package deal like this again.

Sorry about the excitement I showed in my ad by using all the caps and stuff. I just wanted to be a LITTLE different in my wording. Note: send me a request for more photos. I have plenty.  I also am willing to trade for a CUSTOM 1911, or NICE Sig 1911, or perhaps a Presentation Colt 1911. In any case, it's got to be a 1911.  

This VZ is set up in the old Beechwood furniture at the moment. I will type up an instruction guide for the Zahal / FAB assembly if you would like. I will also throw in some ammo and stripper clips. I think I have 12 - 20, and they are holding ammo. This is what I have.

title: For Sale:   #4877 Colt 1860 Army, Second Richards conversion to 44CF, 8”x44SWR, 183XXX
location: Puerto Rico, Puerto Rico, United States
postcontent: 4877 Colt 1860 Army, Second Richards conversion to 44CF, 8”x44SWR, 183XXX serial range with a reproduction “Slim-Jim” holster made by El Paso Saddlery in El Paso, Texas. Correct two line patent dated frame, matching numbers, except for the grips which are excellent replacements and could definitely use some aging to look more in context with the revolver, which has wear and scattered light to heavy pitting and bumps and dings. Some good traces of cylinder scene are still evident and markings are very good and legible. Bore is about a 6 on a scale of 10; it has good deep rifling but does have scattered light to moderate lead build-up and some pitting. However, the action is tight and works fine and it looks like it would shoot very well (after a safety check by a competent gunsmith, of course!) Originally these were 44COLT centerfire chambered, but as that ammo became obsolete, some former owner slightly reamed the chambers and loading port to accept the 44S&W Special (or Magnum) cases , which he then trimmed down to the 44S&W Russian length …as can be seen in the gun. This makes for a VERY easy gun to load for, as 44S&W brass is readily available. Ejector rod head is a home-made functional replacement, but these are available if the new owner decides it needs a better one. The California style Slim-Jim holster is also in very fine condition (being new new) and fits the gun like a glove. The belt loop is fully intact and of course it looks very usable. Sure makes a handsome combination. About G+/VG as described. $2350

title: For Sale:  Colt's Police Positive .38 NP + 6" Barrel and Box circa 1907
postcontent:
This First Issue revolver was manufactured in 1907 based on the serial 15021. It comes with a 2" and 6" barrel and the original box. The original grips are still on it and have been some damage but other than that this 1907 antique Colt is collectable and in great shape. 

The replacement grips cost $28
http://www.midwayusa.com/product/912229/vintage-gun-grips-colt-police-positive-early-style-polymer-black 

Both of Colt's “New Police” rounds were actually slight redesigns of existing S&W cartridges, the .32 S&W Long and .38 S&W with the bullet noses flattened, as Colt resisted providing its main competitor with any free advertising. Colt's Positive Lock safety, the innovation responsible for the gun's introduction, functioned by preventing the firing pin from striking the primer of the cartridge unless the trigger was deliberately pulled. Intended to address deficiencies of earlier models such as the Single Action Army, the Positive Lock prevented an accidental discharge even if the hammer was struck or the pistol was dropped, allowing the revolver to be safely carried with all six chambers loaded
